Review text: "I will start off by saying I am the type of person that generally only writes a review when I am either very pleased with a product or very dissatisfied with a product. That being said overall this is a fine product that is durable and I can see holding up very well. My issue is, I spent an insane amount of time looking for pee chee folders with 3 ring holes punched in them for a binder. It seems like it should be a pretty common item. Unfortunately for me, it is not, so when I found these I was very happy. At least until I opened the box to discover they were not prepunched with 3 holes as described here. This may not be a big deal for some, but it is the only reason I purchased them. So far I have been unsuccessful at getting help in returning or exchanging them which is a first for me with an Amazon prime product. This may sound silly to some or even easily fixable. Just get a hole punch and be done. Well I shouldnt have to spend even more money when I already spent more than I wanted to on these folders just because they didnt provide the product as promised. I am on a fixed income. My whole idea here is to set up one folder for each of my doctors and put them all together in one big 3 ring binder so I can carry them together or separately depending on my needs at the time. I live with chronic illness as result of brain injury and this was supposed to help simplify things. It is the small things we dont think about that can make a big difference in a persons life. Sell it the way you advertise it! Not a difficult concept! If the 3 rings are important to you, do not buy these folders. If this small complaint is no big deal to you and you either do not need the holes or can make your own, then enjoy!"

Review text: The first main selling point about this is that it fits in a looseleaf binder. Well, it’s hole punched for one, but that’s as far as it goes. It’s far too large to actually fit. And there is no reason for that. An 8 ½ x 11 piece of paper sits in the folder with a lot of space above it. Shorter, this would fulfill that part of it’s purpose., The second main selling point is the useful information printed along the side. The way the side is set up, it sits under the paper when the folder is full, so you can’t read all that great information. I mean you could if you rip the perforation, but the first time I tried that it ripped the folder., For what it’s worth, on the left side you get conversion tables (metric, which makes no sense – who need to look up how many kilograms are in a gram?) and the conversion between metric and imperial. You also get a 15 cm ruler. On the right side you get a 6-inch ruler, a 12 x 12 multiplication table, and then a handful of tables: Dry measure conversions (ever wonder how many quarts are in a peck? According to this, 8), Dry measure conversions (expanded? It’s called the same thing but has slightly different information. There are apparently 4 gills in a pint). Avoirdupois weight conversions (this is the 16 ounces in a pound type information), Linear measure table (inches in a foot), circular measure table (minutes in a degree), and surface measure table (square inches in a square foot)., To be fair, I never knew there was a unit of measure called a hogshead before, so it is educational., I needed these to fit in a notebook, and I simply can’t use these.
